When the manuscripts agree, and there is nothing unintelli- gible, it is consistent with the evidence to let‘a passage stand as it is, and it is inconsistent to attempt to improve it. When there is diversity of readings in any ease, we must determine which we will acceptori abalanoe of probabilities. If no reading gives a sufficient sense, we may endeavour to extract from the supposed false readings something which does give a sense and may be what the copiers would have written if they had taken due care. Many excellent corrections have been made in this way, and they commend them· selvas to our judgment as true, that is, as possessing sufficient probability to be accepted as true.

'l'here is another method which we may use in deciding between conflictiug readings, and also in determining whether a passage, where there ia no variation in the readings, may be considered genuine. In the case of Horace, for example, if we study the general purpose of each poem, if we have made ourselves well ac· quaintcd with his manner of expression and his poetic colouring, and if we fix our attention closely on all the words of a given pas· saga, and the connexion of the whole passage with that which precedes and follows, we may often determine with great probability what he intended to write, where the evidence leaves it doubtful; and we may also determine whether critics are justified in putting their own guesses in place of the documentary evidence, when there iano variation in it. The power of justly interpreting is therefore a necessary qualification fora critic who undertakes to settle a text whether ancient or modern; as necessary as it is for the commen- tator who undertakes to explain his author.
